<subsection xml:id="subsec-volume-of-cones" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Volume of Cones</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_e8lnyoep">
            <p xml:id="auto_56ngtsfr">
            <dl>
                <li xml:id="auto_00wmskmq">
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_xvplq848">
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ygqrt2e2">
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_w2p5tkxi">
                        2.8 Volume
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_lyumwp0h">
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_z3om2pyi">
                        Calculate the volume of cones using the formula <m>V = \frac{1}{3} \pi r^2 h</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_5p2nhxft" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_l5x4urny">
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_jamspb8b" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_wdud6k04">
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_hvcarlhz" component="lesson-plan">
                <p xml:id="auto_zrc74rd1"> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li xml:id="auto_lse2ku39">
                        <p xml:id="auto_7xc2f7qt">
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Define a cone and explain why its volume is one-third that of a cylinder with the same base and height.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_kooufo4q">
                        <p xml:id="auto_sbedgw1u">
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Calculate the volume of cones using <m>V = \frac{1}{3} \pi r^2 h</m>, including problems involving slant height.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_1izt2e3k">
                        <p xml:id="auto_pda27cvu">
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Solve real-world problems involving cone volumes, such as ice cream cones, funnels, and conical tents.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
        <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p xml:id="auto_2cs8sig7">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/volume/volume-of-cones.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_t97owroq">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/volume/step-by-step-guide_volume-of-cones.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_pwal1t2i">
            <alert>Expected Time:</alert> 15 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_oi9z1xkh">
            <alert>Grouping:</alert> Organise learners into small groups. Distribute paper/cardboard, scissors, glue/tape, rulers, a cylindrical cup, and empty ice cream cones.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_4xiw8ob2">
            <alert>Method 1 — Paper Cone Construction (5 min):</alert> Guide learners to cut a circle, remove a sector, and roll the remainder into a cone. Ask them to measure the radius and height.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_7gytgid3">
            <alert>Method 2 — Water Pouring Activity (8 min):</alert> Using an ice cream cone and a cylindrical cup with the same height and base, have learners fill the cone with water and pour it into the cylinder repeatedly.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_ro9qda2k">
            <alert>Teacher Facilitation Questions:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_nk2cbidz">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_39r3z4m9">
                    <p xml:id="auto_g9hqsqc6"><q>How many cones of water fill the cylinder?</q> (Expected: 3)</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_yna468u4">
                    <p xml:id="auto_kbk3il0b"><q>So what fraction of the cylinder’s volume is one cone?</q> (Expected: one-third)</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_j1vdtcwe">
                    <p xml:id="auto_y8elj88j"><q>Why does the formula include one-third?</q></p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_sqo2ggbf">
                    <p xml:id="auto_33g58xlc"><q>How is a cone related to a cylinder?</q></p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_j8fygdtt">
            <alert>Expected Discovery:</alert> Learners should articulate that <m>V_{\text{cone}} = \frac{1}{3} V_{\text{cylinder}} = \frac{1}{3} \pi r^2 h</m>.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_a9rnu535">
            <alert>Support for Struggling Groups:</alert> Say <q>Let us count together. How many cones have we poured so far?</q>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_yhax4ldd">
            <alert>Early Finishers:</alert> Ask <q>How would the volume change if the radius doubled? If the height doubled?</q>
        </p>
    </axiom>


        <activity xml:id="auto_a95agfsb">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_qhdo6ra3">
                  Constructing a cone.  
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_l0e1icft">
                    <ol xml:id="auto_2zai2cvb">
                        <li xml:id="auto_mdyln8ro">
                            <p xml:id="auto_ipv0aen6">
                                Materials Needed 
                            </p>
                            <p xml:id="auto_t3giock5">
                                 Sheets of paper or cardboard
                            </p><p xml:id="auto_imkerqsu">
                                 Scissors, glue/tape, and rulers
                            </p>
                            <p xml:id="auto_cqh4k4ja">
                                A cylinder (e.g., cup or bottle) for comparison
                            </p>
                            <p xml:id="auto_pbq7ngmy">
                                <ul xml:id="auto_lhzbczct">
                                    <li xml:id="auto_ozzr3c2x">
                                        <p xml:id="auto_1mjuvl0s">
                                             "How can we turn this into a cone?"
                                        </p>
                                        <p xml:id="auto_3ejbo89j">
                                            Take a piece of paper and <m>\textbf{cut a circle}</m> any radius.
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li xml:id="auto_00thvuz7">
                                        <p xml:id="auto_ouoqtee0">
                                            <m>\textbf{Cut out a sector and roll}</m> the remaining part into a cone shape.
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li xml:id="auto_9dxfutar">
                                        <p xml:id="auto_eqifj6uy">
                                           Measure the radius and height of their cones. 
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li xml:id="auto_nu4691a4">
                                        <p xml:id="auto_hmtgxnun">
                                           Calculate the volume using the formula .
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                </ul>
                            </p>
                            <p xml:id="auto_lint5z3n">
                                <ul xml:id="auto_fw7xomiw" marker="square">
                                    <li xml:id="auto_bbimrwkd">
                                        <p xml:id="auto_cw5kjvk1">
                                            Equally, we can try this activity using; Empty Ice cream cones,  A cylindrical cup of the <m>\textbf{same height}</m> and <m>\textbf{base}</m> as the cone and water.
                                        </p>
                                        <p xml:id="auto_axvcyb97">
                                            <alert>Steps:</alert> 
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li xml:id="auto_298rti3w">
                                        <p xml:id="auto_iuvalpgm">
                                            Fill the cone with water and pour it into the cylinder severally until the cylinder is full.
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li xml:id="auto_euxde5yg">
                                        <p xml:id="auto_f50cy9wi">
                                            How many cones of rice will fill the cylinder?
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li xml:id="auto_6lxba2f9">
                                        <p xml:id="auto_2eefnw36">
                                           <m>\textbf{Notice that it takes exactly 3 full cones to fill the cylinder}</m>.
                                        </p>
                                        <p xml:id="auto_wu79rq83">
                                            This is why the formula includes <m>\frac{\textbf{1}}{\textbf{3}} </m>!
                                        </p>
                                        <p xml:id="auto_lhw28q7y">
                                             <alert>Mathematical Insight</alert></p>
                                           <p xml:id="auto_2lzyh6e3">
                                            ✔ This shows the formula:
                                           </p> <p xml:id="auto_am9947pr"><me> V_\text{cone} = \frac{1}{3} V_\text{cylinder} = \frac{1}{3} \pi r^2h</me>
                                        </p>
                                        <p xml:id="auto_4wi3krys">✔ The cone is one-third of the volume of a cylinder with the same base and height.
                                            
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                
                                </ul>
                            </p>
                        </li>  
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </activity>  
 <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_hu0y9uh1">
            <alert>Expected Time:</alert> 10 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_0nvaxi7v">
            <alert>Transition:</alert> After groups share their findings, formalise the discovery: <q>You discovered that three cones fill one cylinder. That is why the cone volume formula is one-third of the cylinder formula.</q>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_izg52vjf">
            <alert>Key Teaching Points:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_lxlk1rof">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_ig894o4h">
                    <p xml:id="auto_6nd0xb1a">Clearly distinguish between height (perpendicular from base to apex) and slant height (along the curved surface). Use a diagram to show both.</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_kdqmiag7">
                    <p xml:id="auto_tarfl31p">Emphasise the two-step process: (1) Find the base area <m>\pi r^2</m>, (2) Multiply by height and divide by 3.</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_6xwi6quk">
                    <p xml:id="auto_w8a1rb3h">Remind learners that the formula uses the radius, not the diameter. If given the diameter, divide by 2 first.</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_kjhvo2do">
                    <p xml:id="auto_dz36s2cj">Use <m>\pi \approx 3.14</m> or <m>\frac{22}{7}</m> as appropriate. When the radius is a multiple of 7, <m>\frac{22}{7}</m> simplifies the calculation.</p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>
        <insight xml:id="auto_wu4yxy6k">
            <p xml:id="auto_jsy7q4gt">
                <term>What is a Cone?</term> A cone is a three-dimensional solid with a circular base and a curved surface that tapers to a point called the apex or vertex.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_4mg9rag2">
                <term>Formula:</term>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_wy0e41jl">
                Volume of a Cone <m>= \frac{1}{3} \times r^2 \times h</m>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_kvy6x4be">
                Where:
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_1fo78l0a">
                <ol marker="(i)">
                    <li xml:id="auto_u6ty8tgv">
                        <p xml:id="auto_85ohtvai">
                            <m>r</m> is the radius of the circular base
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_sl529uwd">
                        <p xml:id="auto_jt6zvlbc">
                           <m> h</m> is the height of the cone (perpendicular distance from base to apex)
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_iqdrwivq">
                        <p xml:id="auto_08sqhejv">
                            <m>\pi \approx 3.14 \text{or} \frac{22}{7} </m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_j8df6a4y">
                <term>Why <m>\frac{1}{3}</m></term>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_59qpvx4c">
                Three cones with the same base and height fit exactly inside a cylinder with the same base and height. Therefore, the volume of a cone is one-third the volume of a cylinder.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_xfpedjv9">
                <term>Relationship to Cylinder:</term>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_lcdsdoyf">
                <ol marker="(i)">
                    <li xml:id="auto_opn173bp">
                        <p xml:id="auto_kbtubos0">
                            <m>V</m> cylinder <m>= \frac{1}{3} \times V</m> cylinder
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_mgqokjlv">
                        <p xml:id="auto_zeg1mbaj">
                            <m>V</m> cylinder <m>= \pi \times r^2 \times h</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_gobaxbe0">
                        <p xml:id="auto_ka1zbp9b">
                            Therefore, <m>V</m> cone <m>= \frac{1}{3} \times \pi \times r^2 \times h</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_t362yy8o">
                <term>Scaffolding Strategies to Address Misconceptions:</term>
            </p>
            <tabular top="medium" bottom="medium" left="medium" right="medium">
                <row header="yes">
                    <cell>Misconception</cell>
                    <cell>Clarification</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>A cone is the same as a cylinder</cell>
                    <cell> No, a cone has a circular base and tapers to a point, while a cylinder has two parallel circular bases</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>The volume formula is <m>\pi \times r^2 \times h</m></cell>
                    <cell>No, you must multiply by <m>\frac{1}{3}</m></cell>. The formula is <m>\frac{1}{3} \times \pi \times r^2 \times h</m>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>The height is the slant height</cell>
                    <cell>No, the height is the perpendicular distance from the base to the apex, not the slant height along the curved surface</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>I can use the diameter instead of the radius</cell>
                    <cell>No, the formula uses the radius. If you have the diameter, divide by 2 to get the radius</cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </insight> 

